data.detail: Preserved fruit that has been sealed in a can or airtight jar often has a higher amount of sugar and thus more calories as compared to fresh fruit. However, it is possible for canned fruit to have the same calories and nutritional information as its newly harvested counterpart. When picked and preserved during the peak period, canned fruit may even retain a higher percentage of nutrients. All fruits are mostly made of carbohydrates, although calories in canned fruit can also come from fats and small amounts of protein. Fruits are all said to have good nutritional value since they contain a lot of vitamins and minerals per serving, including potassium, phosphorous, and vitamins A and C. Most varieties of fruits that are canned have a naturally high amount of sugar. For example, peaches, pears, and papaya each contain over 40 grams of sugar per 100 grams. If excess sugar has been added during the fruit canning process, that is typically evident by a high number of calories as indicated in the nutrition facts. The calorie chart below can be used as a guideline, but exact amounts for each brand will differ depending on the amount of syrup used, if any.

data.description: Canned fruits have the same calories as fresh ones, but be on the lookout for added syrup.
data.title: Canned Fruit

data.detail: All fruits are mostly made of carbohydrates, although calories in fruit can also come from fats and small amounts of protein. The carbs, however, are not all the same and are usually a mix of complex carbohydrates (i.e., made of three or more bonded sugars) and simple carbohydrates (i.e., simple sugars). This means the amount of glucose and fructose – natural fruit sugars – varies depending on the type of fruit; for example, bananas and figs are high in sugar and taste very sweet, whereas lemons and cranberries are known for a tart flavor due to low sugar content. Regardless of this difference, most fruits are considered to be low-calorie foods. Fruits are all said to have good nutritional value since they contain a lot of vitamins and minerals per serving, and varieties like avocados and coconuts contain healthy fats. It's important to recognize that the high-fat fruits have greater calorie density since a gram of fat has over double the calories of a gram of protein or carbohydrate. Fresh fruits are not sold with nutrition facts. Whether the goal is to limit carb intake, count calories, or simply try to eat more whole food, the calorie chart will pinpoint which fruits best fit into your healthy eating plan.

data.description: Fruit contains many nutrients and natural sugars, but most fruits are not calorie dense.
data.title: Fruits

data.detail: All fruits are mostly made of carbohydrates, although calories in fruit can also come from fats and small amounts of protein. Fruits are all said to have good nutritional value since they contain a lot of vitamins and minerals yet are low-calorie. Prickly pear, which is harvested from a cactus of the same name, are high in magnesium and vitamin C. However, the exact benefits of each tropical and exotic fruit can vary quite a bit. Plantains, although they look a lot like bananas, have a lot more vitamin A and offer more potassium than their yellow counterpart. Some tropical fruits like guava, kiwi, and mango provide a significant amount of healthy fiber, and others like avocados contain healthy omega-3 fatty acids. It's important to recognize that the high-fat fruits have greater calorie density since a gram of fat has over double the calories of a gram of protein or carbohydrate. Since fresh fruits are not sold with nutrition facts, the calorie chart below will help you decide which tropical and exotic fruits fit best into your healthy eating plan.

data.description: Tropical and exotic fruits, including kiwi and bananas, are typically low in calories.
data.title: Tropical & Exotic Fruits

data.detail: A starchy root vegetable, potatoes are high in simple carbohydrates that digest quickly and are metabolized into sugar that the body can burn for energy. However, that does not mean that calories from potato products are always to be avoided in favor of foods with complex carbs. Potatoes have nutritional value due to containing fiber in the vegetable skin, more vitamin C than tomatoes, and more potassium than bananas. It goes without saying, though, that French fries saturated in oil are not the healthiest preparation method; the high calorie density, as indicated by the calorie chart below, reveals a high amount of fat. Other dishes like potato gratin and potato salad can also be high in fat from cheese, butter, and mayonnaise. To avoid excess calories, cook potatoes by boiling in water or baking with a light coating of olive oil. There are many varieties of potatoes and potato products, and the exact nutrition facts regarding carbohydrates, proteins, and micronutrients vary slightly. Red potato skins, for example, contain more antioxidants than that of white varieties. And sweet potatoes beat out the other varieties in terms of vitamin A and calcium, yet have fewer calories.

data.description: Potatoes are a starchy root vegetable with calories mostly from simple carbohydrates.
data.title: Potato Products

data.detail: No doubt about it, vegetables should be a regular part of everyone's diet. One glance at this calorie chart, and it's easy to see why. A large portion of vegetables won't contain very many calories, and yet it will include a wonderful dose of vitamins, minerals, and other nutrients. Vegetables contain a mix of carbohydrates along with smaller amounts of healthy fats and protein. They can also be one of the most valuable sources of dietary fiber; that's one reason why artichokes, starchy veggies like potatoes, and leafy greens like kale have high nutritional value. Superfoods even have an entire day's worth of necessary nutrients. Broccoli packs over twice as much vitamin C as is recommended for daily intake, and believe it or not one medium-sized sweet potato has over 500% the amount of vitamin A needed. Those following a vegetarian or vegan diet should be sure to consume plenty of spinach; there are 3 grams of protein per half cup. What better way is there to add protein to a fresh vegetable salad without racking up the calories? Since fresh fruits are not sold with nutrition facts, the information below will help you decide which veggies fit best into your healthy eating plan.

data.description: Vegetables of all kinds are low in calories and high in nutritional value.
data.title: Vegetables

data.detail: This category of food is named for a popular style of quick-service restaurants, which prepare food in mere minutes and typically have a drive-thru window for cars. Fast food products tend to be very high in calories, and the serving sizes are often larger than what one would cook at home. The number of calories in fast food can be inflated by added fat and sugar, and as with most convenience foods, the products are also loaded with sodium and other preservatives. Fast food menus usually contain items with low nutritional value, or empty calories. French fries are a prime example as they have high calorie density in the form of fat and simple starches; a large order of fries can contain as many calories as the main meal. As shown on the calorie chart, fast food restaurants can also serve lighter fare, for example a salad with grilled chicken, although it's still wise to check the nutrition facts for a high amount of sugar and fat, which can be hidden in salad dressing and other flavorful additions. Detailed nutritional information can often be found in a calorie chart within the restaurant or on the fast food company's website.

list.name: Burger King Double Whopper with Cheese
Burger King Premium Alaskan Fish Sandwich

data.description: Fast food is very high in calories and low in nutrition compared to home-cooked meals.
data.title: Fast Food

data.detail: Although pizza gets a bad rap as a guilty pleasure food, it can have some nutritional value depending on the sauce and toppings. How the pizza crust is made will also affect the number of calories and overall health benefits. Using whole wheat flour instead of white flour increases the amount of complex carbs. This also increases nutrient density, and whole grains are linked to reduced risk of stroke and type 2 diabetes. What you put on top of the pizza makes the biggest difference in overall nutrition of the slice you're eating. High-calorie toppings include cheese, greasy sausage, alfredo (white) sauce, and salamis such as the ever-popular pepperoni. Pizzas with less calories are topped with lots of veggies like peppers, fresh greens like spinach, and mushrooms. Because the number of calories in pizza can vary so widely, this calorie chart should be used as a general guideline, except in the case of specific restaurant items, for example Pizza Hut.

data.description: Everyone thinks pizza is high in calories and fat, but the ingredients can change that.
data.title: Pizza

data.detail: Cheese contains fat and protein, with a very low percentage of calories from carbohydrates. A dairy product, the nutritional value of cheese is similar to that of milk, although cheese has greater calorie density. The ratio of fat to protein depends on the type of cheese, the animal from which the milk was derived, and whether it was made from full-fat or skim milk. On the calorie chart below, high-fat cheeses are indicated by a greater number of calories per ounce, or by a smaller serving size. Cheese is divided into several categories like fresh versus ripened, meaning the cheese undergoes an aging process of weeks to years. It is also classified by texture (in other words, moisture content): soft, semi-soft, and hard. In general, a ripened cheese such as Parmesan is more calorie dense than a fresh variety like cottage cheese. Processed products like American cheese contain a mix of milk fats, whey, cheese cultures, food coloring, and chemical emulsifiers; these are easily spotted by the long list of ingredients in the nutrition facts. Compared to natural cheeses, the processed kind can contain more sodium and saturated fat.

data.description: A dairy product, cheese has similar nutritional value to milk but higher calorie density.
data.title: Cheese

data.detail: This type of cheese is soft and spreadable, and it typically contains a greater amount of calories than other cheeses due to high fat content. However, low-fat varieties like cottage cheese and the French style Neufchatel are not hard to find. These can often be substituted with little loss of flavor in spreads, dips, and desserts like cheesecake and tiramisu. Since cream cheese is a common topping for bagels and other breads, it is often flavored, but as the calorie chart shows, those extra ingredients do not add significant calories. They can include added sugar, though, and a look at the nutrition facts will show how much. All cheeses contain fat and protein, with a very low percentage of calories from carbohydrates. A dairy product, the nutritional value of cheese is similar to that of milk, but even a soft variety like cream cheese is more calorie dense than the original dairy.

data.description: Cream cheese tends to have high fat content, but low-fat versions have fewer calories.
data.title: Cream Cheese

data.detail: Milk is a nutritious liquid that can be harvested from many animals, but the most commonly consumed milk is from cows. Therefore, unless otherwise noted, the dairy products in this calorie chart are made with cow milk. Dairy contains a good balance of fat, carbohydrates, and protein, and it's also a valuable source of calcium, riboflavin, and vitamin B12. Whole milk has equal amounts of fat and protein, but other milk varieties like skim have some or all fat removed, reducing calories as well. On the other hand, dairy products like heavy cream and buttermilk have higher amounts of fat. The main component of milk is lactose, a natural sugar that many people's digestive systems are sensitive to. Vegan plant-based milks, including almond milk and coconut milk, are good substitutes, although they have different nutritional value from animal milk. Check the nutrition label on the carton or can for specific information regarding fats, protein, and carbohydrates in dairy alternatives.

data.description: Dairy milk is nutritious, but options like lower calorie almond milk are becoming popular.
data.title: Milk & Dairy Products

data.detail: Many hard and semi-soft cheeses are sold pre-sliced to be easily used for building sandwiches, or for topping foods like burgers and grilled chicken. One positive of this convenient packaging is that there's no need to worry about portion control; each slice is a single serving. The nutrition value for these sliced cheeses, including Swiss and Emmental, are often the same as the typical pre-sliced version. The calorie chart for cheese has more information about the general nutritional value of these dairy products, including fat content. In some cases, though, sliced cheeses have added ingredients to facilitate the manufacturing process, and varieties like American cheese are processed. These contain a mix of milk fats, whey, cheese cultures, food coloring, and chemical emulsifiers; these are easily spotted by the long list of ingredients in the nutrition facts. Compared to natural cheeses, the processed kind can contain more sodium and saturated fat, but the calories are comparable. Low-fat varieties of sliced cheese can even contain fewer calories than the original.

data.description: The calories in sliced cheeses like Swiss are usually the same as typical cheeses.
data.title: Sliced Cheese

data.detail: This thick, creamy dairy product is made by fermenting animal milk or plant-based milk with specific bacterial cultures. Since yogurt is traditionally made from cow milk, it shares nutritional benefits such as calcium and protein; see the milk and dairy calorie chart for more information. The fermentation process lends yogurt a tangy flavor, but the bacteria are also very good for the digestive system. Yogurt with active cultures, noted near the nutrition facts on the product packaging, can support a healthy immune system. Although yogurt itself is very nutritious, flavored varieties and pre-made parfaits can be loaded with added sugar. Yogurt will have some natural sugar from the dairy, but check the nutrition label to ensure there isn't another teaspoon or more of simple table sugar or corn syrup. This doesn't add many calories but will have a negative effect on blood sugar levels. Start with plain yogurt, and mix in fresh fruits, granola, syrups, and other natural flavorings to control sugar and calorie intake. Yogurt is a recommended substitute for butter or oil in baking, and it can be used in place of mayonnaise and sour cream too. Yogurt can have a lot of calories from fat, but fat-free versions are also widely available.

data.description: Yogurt is a dairy product with calories from protein, natural and added sugars, and fat.
data.title: Yogurt

data.detail: The calories in beef and veal, which are both meat products from cattle, are made up of fat and protein. The percentages of nutrients depends on the exact cut, the part of the animal the meat is from. Check the calorie chart to see which ones have a greater number of calories, thus indicating more fat. That's because one gram of protein equals four calories, whereas one gram of fat has nine. The product or nutrition label, particularly on ground beef, may also represent this nutritional value with percentages such as 85% lean, meaning that 15% is fat. All red meats are a great source of iron and zinc, although beef contains a slightly higher amount of each per serving. However, in terms of B-vitamins like niacin and riboflavin, veal is the better source. Enough of beef and veal calories are from saturated fat, which is why it's recommended to eat only two to four servings (three ounces) a week in a standard healthy diet. Check the nutrition facts to see which varieties of beef fit your dietary needs.

data.description: Beef and veal contain saturated fat and usually have more calories than poultry and fish.
data.title: Beef & Veal

data.detail: Lunch meat calories are primarily in the form of protein, but as the below nutritional information shows, beef and pork products like salami can have just as many calories from animal fat. Thinly sliced cold cuts are a staple ingredient in sandwiches, a simple way to eat lean cuts of baked or roasted turkey, chicken and ham, all of which have high nutritional value. Lunch meats can be high in calories, for example roast beef and various types of sausage, such as bologna. All varieties of lunch meats are commonly served as appetizers alongside sliced vegetables and cheese, as in an antipasto platter. Review the calorie chart to compare servings of popular cold cuts; the higher the calories, the higher the percentage of fat. Most cold cuts are made with the preservative sodium nitrate, the health effects of which are hotly debated. Also check the nutrition facts for artificial flavors, fillers like cornstarch, and added sugar. Although they aren't typically sweet, deli meats often contain honey, maple syrup, or even high fructose corn syrup, as the nutrition label will show.

data.description: The calories in cold cuts are mostly protein, but lunch meats often have fat and nitrates.
data.title: Cold Cuts & Lunch Meat

data.detail: The calories in meats, which are animal products, are primarily in the form of fat and protein. The percentages of nutrients depends on the exact cut, in other words the part of the animal the meat is from. Check the calorie chart to see which meats have a greater number of calories; higher calorie density indicates a higher percentage of fat because one gram of protein equals four calories, whereas one gram of fat has nine. Lean meats, such as chicken breast and white fish, will have the fewest calories per ounce. Red meats, such as lamb and pork, tend to have more calories per ounce. These are also higher in saturated fat, indicating slightly lower nutritional value. Therefore, consumption of red meat is best limited to several times per week. All meat is nutritious since it is an ideal source of protein, containing all essential amino acids. Meat is also one of the best foods for vitamin B12, iron, and zinc. Condiments and marinades can add significant calories to prepared meat; check nutrition facts on sauces and seasonings for more information.

data.description: Meat is a primary source of protein and calories, but meats can also be high in fat.
data.title: Meat

data.detail: Offal refers to the internal organs like the heart and liver, as well as tough parts of the animal like chicken feet and cow tongue. Giblets in particular are organs from poultry, such as found in a whole turkey to be roasted for a holiday like Thanksgiving. In some types of cuisine, these throwaway bits of meat are considered to be delicacies, as with foie gras (goose liver) in France. Although most foods on this calorie chart are unpopular with eaters, research has shown that organ meats have high nutritional value. Brains, for example, have selenium and copper, which are both needed to maintain a healthy immune system. But it carries the risk of mad cow disease, and thus when eating offal, it's important to ensure that the meat is from healthy, grass-fed animals. The diet that livestock eats will affect the nutrition facts of the meat, particularly organs. Since many types of offal are high in fat – tongue is 70% fat – these foods tend to be high in calories as well. Other offal and giblets like the heart and kidneys are lower in fat and calories but are just as good of a source of protein and nutrients.

data.description: Offal and giblets may be discarded, but parts like hearts are low-calorie and nutritious.
data.title: Offal & Giblets

data.detail: This calorie chart lists types of meat that come from pigs, as well as lard, which is rendered pork fat. For each item, the fat and protein ratios vary depending on which part of the animal the meat comes from. Pork belly, the cut that includes bacon and pancetta, is a very fatty meat and therefore also has greater calorie density. Some cuts of bacon can also contain more calories than others depending on thickness; check the nutrition facts on the package for exact amounts. Leaner cuts of pork, meaning parts of the pig with lower fat content and fewer calories, include pork tenderloin. When trimmed, it has the same fat content as skinless chicken breast. However, it's good to know that less than half of the fat in pork is saturated; most of it is beneficial monounsaturated fat. In addition to being a great source of protein, pork also has nutritional value for B-complex vitamins and minerals like zinc and phosphorous.

data.description: Pork, the meat from pigs, can be high in calories like bacon or lean like tenderloin.
data.title: Pork

data.detail: Often recommended as one of the leanest and healthiest varieties of animal protein, this food category includes meat that specifically comes from birds. Poultry refers to domesticated birds that are kept to harvest eggs as well as meat. Fowl is often used to describe game birds that are hunted rather than raised, such as pheasant. Common poultry include chickens, ducks, and turkey, but geese and quail are also eaten frequently in certain cuisine (e.g., French). Large birds such as ostrich and emu, included in the calorie chart, are also farmed. As with all meats, the nutrition facts vary depending on the exact animal and area from which the meat originated. Chicken and turkey breast are commonly recommend for diets as a low-calorie, low-fat source of complete protein. The part of poultry containing the most fat and cholesterol is the skin, and the thighs contain more calories from fat than protein. A majority of the fat from poultry is healthy, though, including monounsaturated fats. The meat from poultry and fowl is therefore a great source of protein for all non-vegetarian diets, but check nutrition label on pre-made meals to look for added calories.

data.description: Chicken and other poultry and fowl are recommended as a lean, low-calorie source of protein.
data.title: Poultry & Fowl

data.detail: A food product made from ground meat, sausage can be created from nearly any kind of animal or vegetarian meat substitute. Therefore, the calorie and fat content can change a lot depending on composition, but all sausages contain a significant amount of complete proteins. For information regarding specific varieties of sausage, first look at the nutritional value of the primary meat, for example chicken or pork. Sausages can be made from any cut of meat, such as lean turkey breast for low-fat sausages, but they are often made from the excess after butchering. Certain types, such as hot dogs and blood sausage, often contain offal like head meat and congealed blood. However, not all sausages are made from these less-desired animal byproducts. Traditionally, sausages are filled intestinal casing, but again, that is not always true. Given that sausage can be made with almost any ingredients, the calorie chart below is to be used as a guideline. Check nutrition labels for specific ingredients and other information, including fat content, calorie density, and indication of preservatives like sodium, which may or may not pose cancer risk when consumed regularly.

data.description: Sausages can be stuffed with any type of meat and therefore vary in calorie density.
data.title: Sausage

data.detail: This calorie chart lists the less common varieties of meat. This is because game meats are typically hunted and are therefore not readily available in supermarkets and other grocery stores. Venison, for example, comes from deer, which are not domesticated or farmed. This category includes very rare meats like alligator and moose, but some foods on the calorie chart, such as lamb and bison, can be found at restaurants and specialty grocers. In general, game meats are rather lean, meaning they contain a higher percentage of protein than fat. But as with all meats, the exact nutritional value will depend on the exact cut. Since this is such an all-encompassing category with mammals, fowl, and even reptiles, the calorie density and other nutrition facts are not standard. The only similar trait of venison and other game is they are all a good source of animal protein. Therefore, these rarer varieties of meat, when available, can fit into a balanced diet, except in case of certain health conditions such as high cholesterol.

data.description: Venison and game meats are a great source of protein with fewer fat calories than beef.
data.title: Venison & Game

data.detail: Cakes and pies often include high-calorie foods like wheat flour, butter, cream, and sugar, which can be viewed separately in the baking ingredients calorie chart. The nutritional value of baked goods tends to be low because the main ingredients provide mostly fats and simple carbohydrates, which can immediately cause rapid fluctuations in blood sugar level and over time lead to increased body weight. However, a portion of calories in pies and cakes can also be from healthy ingredients such as eggs, which contain proteins and nutrients. Many items commonly used when baking pastries like spices and vanilla extract are used in such a small amount that the calories are negligible, but other flavorful additions like tree nuts and dried fruit can boost both nutritional value and calorie density. Packaged cakes and pies, even those labeled “low-fat,” can include high fructose corn syrup, artificial flavors, and artificial sweeteners. Although products marketed as healthy replacements can lower the total calories per serving, these are typically no better (if not worse) than the original recipe. Therefore, it's recommended not to consume pastries on a regular basis and to check nutrition facts on pre-made cake mixes and pies to ensure they fit into your diet.

data.description: Pastries like cakes and pies tend to be calorie-dense to lots of cream, butter, and sugar.
data.title: Cakes & Pies

data.detail: Candy is calorie dense, and it's no surprise that a food group called “sweets” is high in sugar. Those are the two main reasons why these foods are meant to be eaten sparingly in small portions. As with most comforting treats, sweets are not needed for a balanced diet, which means candy and other desserts equal calories, or energy, that would be better derived from ingredients with high nutritional value, such as fruits and vegetables. One glance at the nutrition facts of most candy and sweets would reveal that a majority of calories are in the form of simple sugar. In some cases, the product is 100% sugar, typically the kind that has been processed, as is high fructose corn syrup. Some simple varieties of sweets, including maple candy and rice candy, can be made from raw forms of natural sugar. Other sweet products, like packaged cookies and candy bars, can have a long list of ingredients like canola oil and flavorings. Based on the nutritional information provided in the calorie chart, a candy with low calories per serving is likely pure sugar, and a food with higher calories per serving is a mix of fat and sugar.

data.description: Some candies are low in calories but 100% sugar, whereas other sweets have added fats.
data.title: Candy & Sweets

data.detail: Frozen desserts like ice cream are traditionally calorie dense and contain a high amount of sugar. Ice cream is a dairy product and offers some benefits like calcium and a few grams of protein; check the nutrition facts on the product packaging for exact amounts. That's not to say frozen dairy desserts are a healthy part of a regular diet, though, since most calories in ice cream are in the form of fat and processed sugar. Often ice cream is eaten plain, as with the ever-popular flavors chocolate and vanilla, but it's also common now to include multiple mix-ins like candy and nuts, or toppings like hot fudge. A product with lots of these additional ingredients, for example Snickers ice cream, will likely have a high number of total calories, as indicated on the calorie chart. Items with low calories are made with low-fat milk or, in the case of soft serve, have more air integrated during the mixing process. Ice cream made from alternative vegan milk, such as soy milk and coconut milk, can be found, but these will still contain just as much sugar and therefore also have low nutritional value.

data.description: Ice cream has low nutritional value because it is calorie dense with a lot of sugar.
data.title: Ice Cream

data.detail: Fruit juice calories are almost pure sugar because all of the fiber is removed during the juicing process. Although liquid extracted from fruits contains a lot of micronutrients like vitamins, the calorie chart on this page shows that it contains a lot of calories per serving. Compare the nutrition facts of fruit juice and a soft drink like soda, and it's clear the two have similar amounts of sugar. Unlike refined white sugar (sucrose) and high fructose corn syrup, fruit sugar (fructose) is an all-natural way to combat craving for sweet foods. Fresh fruit juice has nutritional value by providing a wide variety of vitamins, antioxidants, and minerals like zinc, iron, calcium, and magnesium. It's true that the calories in fruit juice can be part of a balanced diet for a healthy, active person, but when limited to 8 ounces daily. Check the nutrition label on the bottle for the serving size and to see if there is added sugar. Especially if you are following a weight loss plan, note on the calorie chart if the amount of juice you are consuming is enough to be considered a snack, much like a whole apple would be.

data.description: Fruit juice has nutrients but is calorie dense, providing energy in the form of sugar.
data.title: (Fruit) Juices

data.detail: The calories in alcohol, including beer and wine, are called empty calories because they do not contain a significant amount of the three macronutrients: protein, fat, and carbohydrates. Alcoholic mixed drinks often have added elements like cola, tonic water, or milk, which can contain macronutrients as well as nutritional value from vitamins and minerals, particularly in the case of juice. However, most cocktails are made using mixers that are high in sugar, which is reflected in the calorie chart as a greater amount of total calories per serving. Nutrition labels reveal that many mixed drinks are also loaded with sugar from syrups. To keep a drink lower in calories, stick to liquor, also called spirits, which are almost pure alcohol due to the distilling process. Alcoholic drinks with a lower percentage of alcohol per volume, such as beer and wine, also have calories from carbohydrates like the wheat in beer and the natural sugar from grapes used to make wine. In general, it is best to avoid all alcoholic beverages on a weight-loss diet and ensure calories come from whole food sources with quality nutrition facts.

data.description: Since alcohol calories have few nutrients, it's best to limit intake for a balanced diet.
data.title: Alcoholic Drinks & Beverages

data.detail: An alcoholic beverage made from fermented cereal grains, beer has calories from both the alcohol and carbohydrates. These are typically called empty calories because they do not contain a significant amount of nutrients that fuel your body's daily functions. Although carbohydrates need to be a significant part of a healthy diet – up to 60% – the carbs in beer are not the ideal source for nutritional value. Some are complex carbs, but beer often contains simple carbs too, which can have a poor effect on blood sugar levels. And since many calories in beer also come from the alcohol, which is used as energy first by your metabolism, the carbs in beer are often turned to sugar and subsequently stored as fat. But not all beer is bad, and the nutritional information will help identify beers that are low in calories and carbs. While some beers can contain 30 grams of carbs per bottle, most light brews and even Guinness contain less than 10 grams per serving. Typically a lower amount of calories, as shown on the calorie chart, indicates fewer carbohydrates. As with any dietary indulgence, beer is best limited to one serving daily, perhaps two or three on occasion.

data.description: Beer, made from fermented grains, contains calories from both alcohol and carbs.
data.title: Beer

data.detail: This calorie chart lists drinks, except alcoholic beverages and pure fruit juice. Non-alcoholic beverages include coffee, soft drinks such as Kool-Aid, and sodas. Liquids can be calorie-free. For example, tap water, many types of tea, and certain diet sodas do not contain calories for the body to metabolize for energy. Other drinks, like regular soda, are high in empty calories. Such soft drinks are easy to consume without getting full, and they are best limited to one serving. Aside from containing water, which should be drank all throughout the day, every day, many beverages do not have significant nutritional value in the form of vitamins and minerals. They can also be very high in added sugar. Even fruit-based drinks such as lemonade can contain high fructose corn syrup. Check the nutrition facts on the bottle or can for specific information; the label will also say if the product like fruit punch contains real fruit juice, and if so, how much.

data.description: Non-alcoholic beverages can be non-caloric, like water and tea, or high calorie like cola.
data.title: Non-Alcoholic Drinks & Beverages

data.detail: Soft drinks such as soda are primarily known for containing a sweetener like sugar along with other flavorings. They are non-alcoholic by themselves but can be used to make mixed drinks, such as rum and Coke. A lot of soft drinks are made from carbonated water, but others like fruit punch are not typically fizzy. Because the common ingredient in soda and soft drinks is often sugar, namely high fructose corn syrup, they are considered to be empty calories. This means that for the amounts of energy listed per serving in the calorie chart, there are very few of the nutrients that your body needs to run like a well-oiled machine. Check the nutrition facts of your favorite soft drink to see. Instead of a can of Fanta fruit-flavored soda, the same number of calories could be consumed as a piece of fruit like a banana, which offers potassium, or an orange, which has lots of vitamin C. Diet sodas will contain fewer calories, but they have a high amount of artificial sweeteners, flavorings, and colorings.

data.description: Soft drinks like soda contain sugar or other sweeteners and are often empty calories.
data.title: Soda & Soft Drinks

data.detail: When fruit juice is fermented and the sugar turns to alcohol, the resulting beverage is called wine. These alcoholic drinks can be made from grapes, but as the calorie chart shows, other types of fruits can be used as well, for example plums. Wine can also be mixed with other ingredients to change the flavor, and this will often increase the amount of calories per ounce, as is the case for chocolate wine. A popular cocktail made with wine, sangria is also on this list, but it can be made with a wide variety of fruit juices and hard liquors. Therefore, the calories indicated below are merely a guideline. For wines that are pure, the nutritional value is relatively similar. Generally, a glass of wine is about 150 to 200 calories, but that can change depending on sweetness, carbonation (as with Prosecco), and alcohol content. A dessert wine like port can have twice as many calories as a standard red table wine and three times as many as a dry white wine. As there are countless varieties and blends of wine, it's recommended to check the nutrition facts on the bottle for exact information.

data.description: The standard glass of table wine has about 150 calories, but sweet varieties have more.
data.title: Wine

data.detail: This calorie chart contains whole grains such as wheat, barley, and corn as well as products made from those simple ingredients, such as pretzels and waffles. While these items can contain different amounts of fat and protein, a bulk of calories in cereal products are in the form of carbohydrates. Due to the health benefits of dietary fiber, such as supporting the digestive system and regulating insulin resistance, it is recommended to consume several servings of whole cereal grains per day. Grains can also contain a significant amount of protein; one cup of cooked amaranth or quinoa has 9 grams of protein. Most cereal products have a very small amount of unsaturated fat, and thus they contain a moderate amount of calories. Much of the nutritional value of cereal grains, including vitamins and fiber, is eradicated when processed to remove the bran, such as with whole wheat flour or corn meal, but this food processing does not remove many calories. The nutrition facts will identify if cereal products have been fortified with vitamins and minerals, and the ingredients list will indicate whether the grains are whole or refined.

data.description: Most calories in whole grains and cereal products come from complex carbohydrates.
data.title: Cereal Products

data.detail: Oatmeal is often a main ingredient in cereals like muesli and granola. Also called rolled oats or old-fashioned oats, plain oatmeal has high nutritional value because it offers lots of complex carbohydrates, some dietary fiber, and significant amounts of vitamin A, vitamin B6, and calcium. One cup of cooked oatmeal also provides 77% of the suggested daily value of iron. The calorie chart below also contains many boxed breakfast cereals, including popular brands like Kellogg's, Post, and Kashi. As with oatmeal, the calories in these products are primarily in the form of carbohydrates. Other grains used to make these cereals include corn, wheat, rice, and barley. Some cereals, such as Multigrain Cheerios, use a blend of grains to offer the health benefits of several staple foods at once. Although oatmeal, muesli, and cereals are great for complex carbs and fiber, it's important to know they can also be packed with extra calories from sugar. Flavored instant oatmeal, for example, can contain 15 grams of sugar per packet. Check the nutrition facts for that and other dietary information, such as which vitamins and minerals each breakfast cereal is fortified with.

data.description: Oatmeal and other cereals offer mostly carbohydrate calories, including dietary fiber.
data.title: Oatmeal, Muesli & Cereals

data.detail: Pasta and noodles are made of a simple mix of flour and water, although they can also contain a binding ingredient like eggs. Because of this basic composition, this food category is almost entirely composed of carbohydrate calories. Common varieties, such as semolina pasta and rice noodles, are often made of simple carbohydrates, meaning they digest quickly and rate higher on the glycemic index. However, whole wheat pasta and brown rice noodles are becoming more readily available; these have more nutrients but the same number of calories. Pasta is a staple of Italian cuisine, and the calorie chart is primarily made of those varieties: spaghetti, penne, rigatoni, fettuccini, etc. These Italian pastas generally have the same nutritional value, and only the shape and size of the product is what differs. Noodles and pasta doughs are also on the calorie chart, including spaetzle, egg noodles, dumpling dough, and pierogi. These items, as well as Italian ravioli, can include more than simple flour, for example a cheese filling. Check the nutrition label for information regarding those ingredients, such as added calories, fat, and protein. To avoid excess calorie consumption, be sure to check the serving size, which may be smaller than you think.

data.description: Since pasta and noodles are made almost entirely of flour, the calories are mostly carbs.
data.title: Pasta & Noodles

data.detail: This category includes common home-cooked dinners like lasagna, popular convenience meals like macaroni and cheese, and restaurant dishes like Peking duck and spring rolls. Dishes and meals are composed of several foods that are cooked together, and thus the total nutritional value can vary quite a lot. To make a meal, foods are combined in a way such that there's a mix of carbohydrates, fats, and protein are combined to help meet the needs of a balanced diet, and because these prepared dishes are made from more than one ingredient, they are often calorie dense. One serving of this side dish contains a significant amount of total daily calories, as the calorie chart on this page indicates. When preparing dishes and meals from scratch, it can be complicated to review the nutrition facts of each individual ingredient; however, a programmed calorie counter (e.g., YAZIO) or recipe analyzer can add up the calories per serving and offer a nutritional breakdown. These tools can make it easier to begin planning and making healthy meals at home rather than relying on packaged foods.

data.description: Calories in dishes and meals are calculated by totaling the nutrition of all ingredients.
data.title: Dishes & Meals

data.detail: A liquid dish eaten with a spoon, soups are often made from a base of stock, bullion, cream, or plain water. Ingredients like vegetables, meats, pasta, rice, and legumes are cooked in boiling water until they become soft, break down, and meld together to infuse the liquid base with flavor. Spices, herbs, and seasoning blends are used to not only make everything else in the soup more delicious, but to help all the ingredients marry. Soups can be simple and thin like chicken broth, hearty with a mélange of ingredients like minestrone, or thick and rich like cream of mushroom. Because soups can be made from practically anything and everything that's edible, the nutrition facts are all across the board. As the calorie chart shows, soups tend to have low calorie density due to high water content, but they can also be made high-fat with cream, butter, coconut milk, and other fatty additions. Soups generally have few calories from proteins, except in the case of some meaty stews.

data.description: Soups are often low in calories, but check the label since any foods can be included.
data.title: Soups

data.detail: Legumes are calorie dense when compared to many other plant products, particularly vegetables, but they are also some of the most nutrient dense foods. The most common categories of legumes are beans and lentils, but other popular foods like peas and peanuts are legumes too; these are grouped with starchy vegetables and fatty tree nuts, respectively, due to nutritional value. That goes to show that calories in legumes come in all forms, and the balance of fat, protein, and carbohydrates is not standard across the category. Legumes also contain valuable plant proteins, and powdered protein supplements are made from soy, peas, and peanuts. The calorie chart is a useful tool for identifying which soy products can be consumed as an alternative to meat. Beans and lentils are also championed as great sources of complex carbohydrates and fiber, and their nutritional profile makes them a worthwhile (and filling!) substitute for meat in a vegetarian diet. Yet, legumes are often packaged in cans, and manufacturers may include additives like salt, sugar, and chemicals like calcium chloride to preserve texture; check nutrition facts to be sure the product is pure, or use dried beans.

data.description: Beans and other legumes are nutritional foods with calories from carbs, fat, and protein.
data.title: Legumes

data.detail: Nuts and seeds contain a high amount of calories considering they are such small foods and are consumed in small portions. Most ingredients in this category are primarily composed of fats, along with varying degrees of protein and carbohydrates. Tree nuts like almonds and edible seeds like from the chia plant are among the best whole food sources of omega-3 fats. These fatty acids, along with omega-6, are listed on nutrition facts as polyunsaturated fats. When your diet includes a good balance of these two omega fats, it helps regulate blood cholesterol levels and may even lower the risk of developing type 2 diabetes. The calorie chart also contains legumes like peanuts, peas, and soy beans, which are the seeds or fruit of plants in the legume family; these are good sources of plant protein. Except in cases of tree nut/peanut allergies and other rare health concerns, seeds and nuts are recommended for all diets due to high nutritional value. Nuts and seeds are highly versatile ingredients that can be used whole or ground. Add a spoonful of seeds or handful nuts to salads, sauces, breads, garnishes, smoothies, and desserts, but be careful not to overindulge and add too many calories.

data.description: Nuts and seeds are high in fat and therefore calorie dense, but they are very nutritious.
data.title: Nuts & Seeds

data.detail: Calories from oils and fats, as the category name states, are usually all from fat rather than carbohydrates or protein. This does not mean, however, that these food products included in this calorie chart are unhealthy. Fat should make up a significant part of every balanced diet, regardless of personal needs, and may account for 20% to 40% of total daily calorie intake. Some diet plans, such as Atkins and Paleo, emphasize eating healthy fats from nuts, olives, hemp, sunflower, and avocados. Oils extracted from these sources are recommended for cooking. Even real butter can be a healthy source of fat as long as consumption isn't excessive. For example, a pat of pure butter on toast is acceptable for most people, except when a doctor or dietician has recommended limited cholesterol intake. The best fats are polyunsaturated and monounsaturated, whereas trans fats should be avoided at all times; check nutrition facts to distinguish which types of oils and fats are in your favorite foods.

list.name: I can\'t believe it\'s not Butter

data.description: Calories from oils are pure fat, but certain varieties like avocado are heart-healthy.
data.title: Oils & Fats

data.detail: This calorie chart lists oils that are derived from plants, including vegetables and also fruits. This is complementary to the category of animal fats; the amount of fat calories is similar, but the origin of the products differs. Therefore, these oils are suitable for vegetarian and vegan diets. Although oils are essentially pure fat and have comparable calorie density, the micronutrient content changes depending on the fruit or vegetable from which the oil was extracted. Vegetable oil is said to be the essence of a plant, and as such it does carry some of the same health properties as the whole plant. Walnut oil, for example, has phytonutrients to help balance hormones, as well as skin-improving vitamins and antioxidants. Ever-popular olive oil has natural anti-inflammatories and significant amounts of vitamins E and K. Mix up the vegetable oils you use in the kitchen for the most nutritional value, and look at the nutrition facts to ensure what you're buying is pure.

data.description: Vegetable oils have the same calories as animal fat but are suitable for all diets.
data.title: Vegetable Oils

data.detail: Common baking ingredients include high-calorie foods like wheat flour, butter, and sugar. The nutritional value of baked goods tends to be low because these ingredients provide mostly fats and simple carbohydrates, which can contribute to rapid fluctuations in blood sugar level and increased body weight. However, some baking ingredients including eggs can be very nutritious since they contain good proteins and nutrients like choline and lutein. Other items common in baking, like cinnamon and yeast, are used in such a small amount that the calories are negligible, but these flavorings and leavening agents offer unique health benefits. Although the calorie chart shows they add little in the way of energy, common spices are known to have anti-inflammatory, weight loss, and disease-fighting properties, and baker's yeast contains nutrients like B-complex vitamins, zinc, and potassium. Low-calorie or calorie-free baking ingredients also include artificial sweeteners or sugar replacers, for example sucralose and stevia. Research has shown that chemical sweeteners can be harmful to one's health and can worsen sugar cravings; therefore, these should be consumed minimally. Check nutrition labels on pre-made cake mixes and other packaged baking ingredients to ensure they fit into your diet.

data.description: Baking ingredients can contain a lot of calories, like sugar, or very little, like spices.
data.title: Baking Ingredients

data.detail: The total calories in a serving of seafood can vary widely, as nutrition facts show, because the category includes various types of meat sourced from a river, ocean, or other body of water. Like poultry and red meat, fish and other water dwellers are very low in carbohydrates, but the amounts of fat and protein differs from one type of seafood to the next. In the calorie chart, types of fish that show high calorie density, including salmon and tuna, will have a greater amount of fat per serving. However, it's important to note that seafood contains healthy fats, such as omega-3 fatty acids; these offer so many benefits that fish oil is a common dietary supplement, but the best source is the whole food. In general, fish and seafood are very lean meats, meaning that almost all calories come from protein. This category of food, when prepared in a healthful way, has such great nutritional value that fish and seafood are recommended as a regular part of any balanced diet, so much so that many people who are drawn to a vegetarian lifestyle follow a pescatarian diet, foregoing all meat except seafood.

data.description: Fish and seafood are often low in fat and therefore calories, providing mostly protein.
data.title: Fish & Seafood

data.detail: The calories in herbs and spices are often negligible in a finished dish because they are used in small amounts, like a dash of cinnamon or tablespoon of dried basil. In a recipe with many servings, however, it can be necessary to consider the calories coming from herbs and spices. A few items on the calorie chart add significant calories even in small portions due to processing, such as adding sugar to make crystallized ginger. Many spice blends, including poultry seasoning, can also contain a lot of salt; check nutrition facts for exact sodium and sugar values. Table salt, listed on the calorie chart as iodized salt, is not calorie dense but can have a negative effect on health (e.g., increasing blood pressure) when the recommended daily value of about 2000 mg is exceeded. Herbs and spices are primarily used to add flavor without increasing total calories, but these ingredients often have health benefits as well. Chili peppers, for example, have high nutritional value because they contain capsaicin, which releases endorphins and acts as an anti-inflammatory, and tarragon is a rich source of antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals like calcium and iron.

data.description: Herbs and spices often add negligible calories to a meal but offer high nutritional value.
data.title: Herbs & Spices

data.detail: This calorie chart lists a wide variety of flour-based baked goods, including loaves of bread, flatbreads like pita and naan, small rolls, and other pastries. Many types of basic breads have similar nutritional value because the dough is a similar mixture of wheat flour and eggs, but the exact ratios may vary. The ingredients, particularly yeast, also affect the density of bread. So you can eat the same size piece of a bagel and focaccia, but the former will have more calories. Sandwich breads and rolls can also have seeds and whole grains added, which increase calories but also nutrient density. Pastries such as croissants, scones, and pie dough also contain a lot of butter or oil, which contributes fat and thus more calories per serving. They are regularly garnished or filled with nuts, fruit, chocolate, and icing, which all add significant calories and often sugar too. Check the nutrition information of baked products for added sugar, especially in the form of high fructose corn syrup.

data.description: Breads like sprouted wheat are very nutritious, whereas pastries can be empty calories.
data.title: Pastries, Breads & Rolls

data.detail: This calorie chart contains food items that, although never meant to be eaten alone, can add significant calories to a dish. It is therefore important to not just consider the nutritional value of the main part of the meal, for example noodles or chicken breast, but to also add the calories from sauces and dressings as well. Because the name of this food group describes a part of the dish rather than the shared ingredients, the nutrition facts of sauces and dressings can vary widely. Some have hardly any calories but add significant taste, such as tabasco sauce, whereas other sauces and dressings have greater calorie density, such as full-fat sour cream. Even though many salad dressings and marinades are low-calorie and have small serving sizes, they can contain a lot of added fat and sugar. Condiments can be sweetened with high fructose corn syrup; one example of this is ketchup. Review the nutrition label and ingredients for more information. To limit added calories in an otherwise nutritious meal, it's best to use salad dressings sparingly, particularly if the base is olive oil.

data.description: Sauces and dressings seem like a small addition but can add significant calories.
data.title: Sauces & Dressings

data.detail: This calorie chart contains food items that, although never meant to be eaten alone, can add significant calories to the food item they are accompanying, for example toasted bread or crackers. It is therefore important to not just consider the nutritional value of the main ingredients but to also add the calories from spreads as well. Because the name of this food group describes a part of the appetizer or meal rather than the shared ingredients, the nutrition facts of spreads can vary widely. Some of the most popular types, including peanut butter and olive tapenade, are primarily made of fat calories due to high natural oil content. On the other hand, many spreads like marshmallow, honey, and jam are almost pure sugar. The calories in sweet spreads are therefore mostly in the form of simple carbohydrates. It may not seem like you're slathering on a large portion of your favorite spread, but be sure to watch how fast the jar empties. Spreads are typically very calorie dense, and it's easy to consume too much in one sitting. Check the nutrition label for more detailed information on suggested serving sizes.

data.description: Spreads are calorie dense, whether they are mostly fat like tapenade or sugar like honey.
data.title: Spreads
